Notebook[{
Cell["\<\
Prehensile tails are mobile limbs with the ability to grasp objects and \
provide support and stability to organisms such as primates, chameleons, and \
seahorses. Robotics researchers have studied prehensile tails for \
applications in three dimensional body rotation movements and adding balance \
to quadrupeds and real-world elderly citizens. However, determining the joint \
configurations for robotic tails is a challenging computational problem \
involving mechanics, geometry, and tuning. To address this issue, I present \
an algorithm to compute the exact positioning for a prehensile tail with a \
specified joint mass, number, and length which balances out a counterweight \
of any given height and mass.\
\>", "Abstract",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.992599323395426*^9},ExpressionUUID->"ddc80b25-67ec-4d48-b40b-\
487a026c1121"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Introduction", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992443330238624*^9, 
  3.992443336737669*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2f4ee309-59a2-4423-9ddf-\
bdae105e856a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Role of Prehensile Tails", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992443338678629*^9, 3.9924433402969913`*^9}, {
  3.992548732435772*^9, 3.9925487360213327`*^9}, {3.992548782794079*^9, 
  3.992548801228258*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"37716ee0-6ae0-4a4d-bcf1-\
493b5ebcaeb6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Prehensile tails are defined as a tail that has evolved to take an active \
role more like an independent leg, similar to arms or legs. They can be found \
in all classes of animals and each takes a different role. Starting as early \
as the dinosaurs, while not prehensile, tails in general begun to take an \
active role in theropods, where paleontologists proposed that they use their \
tails as dynamic stabilizers which enhance speed. The same study also \
examined how the ",
 StyleBox["Agama",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " lizards swing their tails when airborne in jumps to reduce rotational \
movement (Libby et al., 2012). In chameleons, scientists have discovered \
through analyzing bone evolution and angles of 28 species that in both their \
prehensile and non-prehensile tails, tails are used for flexibility and \
stiffening front torsos for balancing (Molnar & Watanabe, 2023). On the other \
hand, scientists have discovered that seahorses, such as the ",
 StyleBox["Hippocampus kuda,",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " curl their tails downward in order to exert forces and grip other objects \
(Hale, 1996)."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992548803199799*^9, 3.9925488050973663`*^9}, 
   3.992549292314377*^9, {3.99254948992769*^9, 3.992549509391876*^9}, {
   3.9925495665773773`*^9, 3.992549619143268*^9}, {3.9925496722727623`*^9, 
   3.992549676444132*^9}, {3.99254971588214*^9, 3.992549733957552*^9}, {
   3.992549786484432*^9, 3.992549794880673*^9}, {3.992549827712153*^9, 
   3.992549834200429*^9}, {3.992549907983307*^9, 3.9925499833518047`*^9}, {
   3.9925500643330593`*^9, 3.992550070122388*^9}, {3.992550108511402*^9, 
   3.9925501573482647`*^9}, {3.992550206670268*^9, 3.992550209377697*^9}, {
   3.992550251081251*^9, 3.992550252903345*^9}, {3.992550301060635*^9, 
   3.992550354970546*^9}, {3.992550388331648*^9, 3.992550468260149*^9}, {
   3.992550715785241*^9, 3.992550721554553*^9}, {3.992550879200548*^9, 
   3.99255104675781*^9}, {3.9925510780880117`*^9, 3.992551124596857*^9}, {
   3.992551463826867*^9, 3.992551606056014*^9}, {3.9925518050802803`*^9, 
   3.9925518701474648`*^9}, {3.992551909683261*^9, 3.992551953298626*^9}, {
   3.992551992308588*^9, 3.992552024267477*^9}, {3.992552135243115*^9, 
   3.992552182694838*^9}, {3.992552247474331*^9, 3.992552252953891*^9}, {
   3.992556267271801*^9, 3.992556372058043*^9}, {3.992598653323943*^9, 
   3.992598654821154*^9}, 3.992599875353657*^9, {3.9925999329563236`*^9, 
   3.9925999809237175`*^9}, {3.9926000637487583`*^9, 
   3.9926001528440285`*^9}, {3.992600206367216*^9, 3.9926002582423477`*^9}, {
   3.992600290601425*^9, 
   3.9926004008040295`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f4929acc-f107-4e97-af48-\
249a676480ed"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Monkeys, a species of animals most similar to humans, are an example of \
prehensile tail use. When examining kinematic data of species ",
 StyleBox["Ateles",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["Lagothrix",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", researchers found that the tails of ",
 StyleBox["Ateles ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "have",
 " larger attachment sites for muscles, less side-to-side sway, and stronger \
locomotion (Schmitt et al., 2005). For other monkeys, such as the ",
 StyleBox["Potos flavus ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "and ",
 StyleBox["Alouatta macconnelli",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", specialization once again plays a role. The ",
 StyleBox["P. flavus ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "uses its tail for postural behaviors and grabbing large objects, while ",
 StyleBox["A. macconnelli ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "uses its tail for grabbing small objects, mass bearing, and stability. In a \
non-monkey species, the Kinkajou ",
 StyleBox["Sapajus apella",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " uses its tail for both posture and stability (Naas et al., 2025)."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992548803199799*^9, 3.9925488050973663`*^9}, 
   3.992549292314377*^9, {3.99254948992769*^9, 3.992549509391876*^9}, {
   3.9925495665773773`*^9, 3.992549619143268*^9}, {3.9925496722727623`*^9, 
   3.992549676444132*^9}, {3.99254971588214*^9, 3.992549733957552*^9}, {
   3.992549786484432*^9, 3.992549794880673*^9}, {3.992549827712153*^9, 
   3.992549834200429*^9}, {3.992549907983307*^9, 3.9925499833518047`*^9}, {
   3.9925500643330593`*^9, 3.992550070122388*^9}, {3.992550108511402*^9, 
   3.9925501573482647`*^9}, {3.992550206670268*^9, 3.992550209377697*^9}, {
   3.992550251081251*^9, 3.992550252903345*^9}, {3.992550301060635*^9, 
